      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE COMPARISON -->
    <section class="why" id="compare">
      <div class="why-inner">
        <p class="section-eyebrow">What each one actually does</p>
        <h2 class="section-headline">
          Four products. Three different jobs. One of them is odor.
        </h2>
        <p class="section-sub">
          The reason the aisle is confusing is that these products aren't
          competing — they're doing different things. Once you know which job you
          actually need done, the choice gets simple.
        </p>
        <div class="why-grid">
          <div class="why-card">
            <h3>Foot powder — the moisture job</h3>
            <p>
              Absorbs sweat and keeps skin dry for a few hours. It genuinely does
              that. But it's managing moisture, not odor, and it cakes into socks
              and linings. The smell in your shoes is untouched.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="why-card">
            <h3>Antiperspirant — the sweat job</h3>
            <p>
              Reduces how much you sweat in the first place. If sheer sweat
              volume is your issue, that's the right tool. It is not a
              deodorizer, and it does nothing about odor already living in your
              footwear.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="why-card">
            <h3>Foot soak — the reset job</h3>
            <p>
              Cleans and resets the skin, and it feels great. It also takes
              twenty minutes and treats exactly one half of the problem. Your
              shoes are not in the tub with you.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="why-card">
            <h3>Fragrance spray — the cover job</h3>
            <p>
              Layers scent on top of the smell. Lasts about an hour, then the two
              combine into something worse than where you started. Adds nothing,
              addresses nothing.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="why-card featured-card">
            <h3>JockShock — the odor job</h3>
            <p>
              Goes after the source of the smell instead of masking it, and it
              sprays into the shoes and boots where the odor actually
              accumulates. No powder, no residue, no fragrance. Safe on skin
              contact.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="why-card">
            <h3>What we don't do</h3>
            <p>
              We don't reduce sweating — that's an antiperspirant's job, and if
              that's your issue, go get one. We're a deodorizer. We handle the
              smell.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- WHY THEY ALL MISS -->
    <section class="wo">
      <div class="wo-inner">
        <p class="section-eyebrow">The thing they all miss</p>
        <h2 class="section-headline">
          Every one of them treats your feet. None of them treat your shoes.
        </h2>
        <div class="wo-grid">
          <div class="wo-card">
            <h3>The odor isn't only on you</h3>
            <p>
              Your feet sweat into socks, insoles, and linings all day. That's
              where the odor accumulates and concentrates — over weeks, over a
              whole season.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="wo-card">
            <h3>Clean feet get reloaded</h3>
            <p>
              Powder them, soak them, scrub them — then put them back in the same
              shoes. Within minutes the odor transfers right back. You've been
              cleaning one end of a loop.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="wo-card">
            <h3>That's why it always returns</h3>
            <p>
              It isn't that the product failed. It's that half the problem was
              never in the room. Treat the footwear and the feet together and the
              cycle finally breaks.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE ROUTINE -->
    <section class="how" id="routine">
      <div class="how-inner">
        <p class="section-eyebrow">The routine</p>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Thirty seconds, both ends of the loop.</h2>
        <ol class="how-steps">
          <li>
            <span class="step-n">1</span>
            <div>
              <h3>Spray the feet</h3>
              <p>
                Light mist — tops, soles, between the toes. Safe on skin contact,
                dries without powder or residue.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="step-n">2</span>
            <div>
              <h3>Spray inside the shoes</h3>
              <p>
                The insole and the lining. This is the step the powder, the soak,
                and the soap all skip — and it's where the odor lives.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="step-n">3</span>
            <div>
              <h3>Air dry, out of the bag</h3>
              <p>
                Don't zip damp shoes into a gym bag. Let them breathe. Dry
                footwear is most of the battle.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="step-n">4</span>
            <div>
              <h3>Repeat after wear</h3>
              <p>
                Thirty seconds after practice and the smell never rebuilds to
                where it was.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq">
      <div class="faq-inner">
        <p class="section-eyebrow">Common questions</p>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Quick answers.</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          {
            FAQ_ITEMS.map((item) => (
              <details class="faq-item">
                <summary>
                  <span class="faq-q">{item.q}</span>
                  <span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">
                    +
                  </span>
                </summary>
                <p class="faq-a">{item.a}</p>
              </details>
            ))
